JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: 10 years ago?

00:40:22.980 --> 00:40:23.664
OK.

00:40:23.664 --> 00:40:24.580
So it's changed a lot.

00:40:27.670 --> 00:40:29.470
Tanzania is an
interesting example,

00:40:29.470 --> 00:40:33.170
because there is
harmony in Tanzania.

00:40:33.170 --> 00:40:35.740
Which there is not in
many African countries.

00:40:35.740 --> 00:40:39.270
There's a sense of national
identity in Tanzania, which

00:40:39.270 --> 00:40:41.270
there is not in many countries.

00:40:41.270 --> 00:40:44.410
But Tanzania is really poor,
and Tanzania will always

00:40:44.410 --> 00:40:46.900
be behind Kenya and some
of the other countries

00:40:46.900 --> 00:40:51.340
in that region because of
its history of socialism.

00:40:51.340 --> 00:40:54.310
And some of it failed really
bad, like these forced forms

00:40:54.310 --> 00:40:55.440
and things.

00:40:55.440 --> 00:40:59.050
It was kind of like
the Great Leap Forward.

00:40:59.050 --> 00:41:00.560
But they got some things right.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:05.660
And their governance-- so their
economic policy was really bad.

00:41:05.660 --> 00:41:11.200
But they got some political and
social issues absolutely right.

00:41:11.200 --> 00:41:14.560
And that was, "let's think
of ourselves as Tanzanian.

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:17.620
For better or for worse, we're
stuck in the same space that's

00:41:17.620 --> 00:41:19.060
called Tanzania."

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:21.162
We can complain
about colonialism.

00:41:21.162 --> 00:41:22.870
We can look back and
say, "you know what?

00:41:22.870 --> 00:41:27.040
It makes no sense that that
Maasai 50 yards away from me

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:28.900
is a Kenyan and
we are Tanzanian."

00:41:28.900 --> 00:41:32.650
Because those lines went
right through ethnic areas.

00:41:32.650 --> 00:41:34.120
But that's the way it goes.

00:41:34.120 --> 00:41:36.130
And the African Union
actually made a decision

00:41:36.130 --> 00:41:38.470
in the '60s, when
it started, not

00:41:38.470 --> 00:41:41.050
to revisit colonial borders.

00:41:41.050 --> 00:41:44.440
Because it would be
this endless problem.

00:41:44.440 --> 00:41:46.570
There would be disputes
all over the continent,

00:41:46.570 --> 00:41:48.580
because none of those
borders make sense.

00:41:48.580 --> 00:41:51.040
So the Tanzanians
did something smart.

00:41:51.040 --> 00:41:53.410
The first president,
Julius Nyerere.

00:41:53.410 --> 00:41:55.740
And he said, "we're Tanzanian.

00:41:55.740 --> 00:41:58.150
Everybody's gotta
speak Swahili."

00:41:58.150 --> 00:42:00.340
No local language.

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:01.690
You've gotta to speak Swahili.

00:42:01.690 --> 00:42:06.910
And to enforce that, they did
it was almost like desegregation

00:42:06.910 --> 00:42:07.840
busing.

00:42:07.840 --> 00:42:09.700
They took kids from
Western Tanzania

00:42:09.700 --> 00:42:12.290
and they sent them to Eastern
Tanzania for high school,

00:42:12.290 --> 00:42:14.920
or from the north to the south.

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:17.410
They mixed mix
people up, so there

00:42:17.410 --> 00:42:19.480
was no way to just get
comfortable in your area

00:42:19.480 --> 00:42:21.370
and only speak your
local language.

00:42:21.370 --> 00:42:24.280
And to this day, like I
studied Swahili in college,

00:42:24.280 --> 00:42:26.980
and in Tanzania, it's
beautiful Swahili.

00:42:26.980 --> 00:42:28.930
That's their national language.

00:42:28.930 --> 00:42:32.920
And that permeated more than
just a linguistic issue.

00:42:32.920 --> 00:42:35.592
It resulted in more
social cohesion.

00:42:35.592 --> 00:42:38.050
And Tanzania has no history--
it's one of the few countries

00:42:38.050 --> 00:42:39.010
in Africa--

00:42:39.010 --> 00:42:41.860
literally, there's
very, very few

00:42:41.860 --> 00:42:44.560
out of all those 54
countries with no history

00:42:44.560 --> 00:42:47.120
of ethnic conflict.

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:50.200
So that's an example of
some very good governance,

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:52.495
but they did disastrous
economic policy,

00:42:52.495 --> 00:42:55.120
where they said everybody should
live on these collective farms

00:42:55.120 --> 00:42:55.930
and work together.

00:42:55.930 --> 00:42:58.990
And the productivity went
down, and people starved.

00:42:58.990 --> 00:43:02.500
It was just all that we
know from history shows that

00:43:02.500 --> 00:43:05.290
doesn't work.

00:43:05.290 --> 00:43:08.470
I think Tanzania is one
of the signs of hope,

00:43:08.470 --> 00:43:12.340
because that cohesion
and stability is there.

00:43:12.340 --> 00:43:15.400
I don't think anything
is going to shake that up

00:43:15.400 --> 00:43:17.590
in the near term.

00:43:17.590 --> 00:43:19.330
Kenya's very hopeful too.

00:43:19.330 --> 00:43:20.950
It's just messy, politically.

00:43:20.950 --> 00:43:22.420
It's very ethnic.

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:25.570
I can look at somebody's
ID, see their name,

00:43:25.570 --> 00:43:27.890
and have a 90%
chance of guessing

00:43:27.890 --> 00:43:29.140
who they're going to vote for.

00:43:29.140 --> 00:43:32.152
Because I can tell their
tribe by their name, and I'll

00:43:32.152 --> 00:43:33.610
know who they're
going to vote for.

00:43:33.610 --> 00:43:36.640
Because people vote,
like almost everybody

00:43:36.640 --> 00:43:39.350
in that country except a
few urban intellectuals,

00:43:39.350 --> 00:43:41.860
will vote for the
person of their tribe.

00:43:41.860 --> 00:43:44.500
And that results in all this
kind of crappy politics.

00:43:44.500 --> 00:43:50.500
Because if you have a corrupt
leader, a corrupt politician,

00:43:50.500 --> 00:43:52.300
and he's from your
ethnic group, you're

00:43:52.300 --> 00:43:55.540
going to vote for him,
because he's your guy.

00:43:55.540 --> 00:43:57.850
And so these guys
get away with murder.

00:43:57.850 --> 00:43:59.623
Like, the salaries
in Kenya, this

00:43:59.623 --> 00:44:00.870
is a really interesting fact.

00:44:00.870 --> 00:44:03.640
The MPs, the members
of parliament in Kenya,

00:44:03.640 --> 00:44:06.650
make something like
$200,000 a year.

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:10.200
So in absolute terms, they
are some of the highest paid

00:44:10.200 --> 00:44:12.340
lawmakers in the world.

00:44:12.340 --> 00:44:18.250
If you compare it relative to
the per capita national income,

00:44:18.250 --> 00:44:20.680
average income, it would
be like a congressman

00:44:20.680 --> 00:44:22.510
making like $20 million a year.

00:44:22.510 --> 00:44:24.880
Because the average income
in Kenya is like $800.

00:44:24.880 --> 00:44:26.740
These guys make $200,000.

00:44:26.740 --> 00:44:28.720
If you look at the
American average income

00:44:28.720 --> 00:44:31.000
and then project it
out by the same factor,

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:34.480
it would be like a congressman
making $40 million a year.

00:44:34.480 --> 00:44:35.996
They keep getting elected.

00:44:35.996 --> 00:44:37.120
People vote for these guys.

00:44:37.120 --> 00:44:38.286
They give themselves raises.

00:44:38.286 --> 00:44:41.020
It's all because of
the ethnic politics.

00:44:41.020 --> 00:44:43.297
So some of that has deep roots.

00:44:43.297 --> 00:44:45.130
It was the way these
countries were created.

00:44:45.130 --> 00:44:46.120
They're young.

00:44:46.120 --> 00:44:49.720
Most of the countries in Africa
are less than 60 years old.

00:44:49.720 --> 00:44:52.690
America was a mess 60 years in.

00:44:52.690 --> 00:44:56.500
That's when brother was killing
brother in the US civil war.

00:44:56.500 --> 00:44:58.460
So you gotta keep that in mind.

00:44:58.460 --> 00:45:00.640
It's not an excuse, but
it brings up this issue

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:02.710
of what's the yardstick.

00:45:02.710 --> 00:45:06.430
Do we hold them to the same
standards as our countries?

00:45:06.430 --> 00:45:09.250
Or do we hold them to their
own relative standards?

00:45:09.250 --> 00:45:10.570
Or something in between?

00:45:10.570 --> 00:45:11.860
Because you don't want
to get to relative.

00:45:11.860 --> 00:45:13.420
Like, what's happened
in South Sudan

00:45:13.420 --> 00:45:15.010
with people
slaughtering each other

00:45:15.010 --> 00:45:17.095
is absolutely
wrong in all cases.

00:45:19.840 --> 00:45:21.460
So I think governance is key.

00:45:21.460 --> 00:45:23.320
And then there
are a few examples

00:45:23.320 --> 00:45:27.230
of good central planning
but repressive governments.

00:45:27.230 --> 00:45:30.580
So like Rwanda, very
good poverty programs,

00:45:30.580 --> 00:45:32.200
very good development programs.

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:36.230
Rwanda is this tiny little
country packed with people.

00:45:36.230 --> 00:45:38.230
It's one of the most
densely populated countries

00:45:38.230 --> 00:45:39.710
in the world.

00:45:39.710 --> 00:45:40.840
And that's a problem.

00:45:40.840 --> 00:45:43.870
And so they've got to be really
smart how they use their land,

00:45:43.870 --> 00:45:48.610
where they put their roads,
everything, family planning.

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:50.170
And they're doing
it, but there's

00:45:50.170 --> 00:45:51.880
almost no freedom in Rwanda.

00:45:51.880 --> 00:45:54.940
If you have a difference of
opinion, you're thrown in jail

00:45:54.940 --> 00:45:56.860
or killed.

00:45:56.860 --> 00:45:59.760
And so that's the choice
a lot of Africans have.

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:00.970
It's not even a choice.

00:46:00.970 --> 00:46:04.510
That's the two alternatives
that they face.

00:46:04.510 --> 00:46:07.690
It's either a really shitty
kind of crazy government that

00:46:07.690 --> 00:46:10.570
doesn't care about you,
but you have some freedom,

00:46:10.570 --> 00:46:14.320
or a government that's not
bad about improving your water

00:46:14.320 --> 00:46:17.980
or giving your kids school
or a road that you can use,

00:46:17.980 --> 00:46:20.954
but you have no freedom.

00:46:20.954 --> 00:46:21.745
Not a great choice.

