00:48:44.631 --> 00:48:46.380
They're getting calls
from their villages,

00:48:46.380 --> 00:48:47.920
they're talking to their wives.

00:48:47.920 --> 00:48:51.150
That little improvement in
their disposable income,

00:48:51.150 --> 00:48:53.430
their salaries have gone
up, the cell phone costs

00:48:53.430 --> 00:48:54.900
have gone down.

00:48:54.900 --> 00:48:56.610
They might not be
quite middle class,

00:48:56.610 --> 00:48:58.830
but they're gainfully employed.

00:48:58.830 --> 00:49:00.600
Their lives are getting
a little better.

00:49:00.600 --> 00:49:05.100
They now have enough money to
talk to their people back home.

00:49:05.100 --> 00:49:07.860
So that stuff, the
development is happening.

00:49:07.860 --> 00:49:08.940
You're seeing it.

00:49:08.940 --> 00:49:14.940
Sometimes, we're like exporting
the wrong stuff, I would say.

00:49:14.940 --> 00:49:16.410
You know, there's
Domino's Pizza.

00:49:16.410 --> 00:49:17.640
There's Burger King.

00:49:17.640 --> 00:49:19.260
There's Coldstone Creamery.

00:49:19.260 --> 00:49:23.850
You know, this kind of like
high cal, unhealthy food.

00:49:23.850 --> 00:49:25.860
Kenyans actually eat pretty--

00:49:25.860 --> 00:49:27.660
everything there
is very natural,

00:49:27.660 --> 00:49:31.650
because like fast food
hasn't, up until recently,

00:49:31.650 --> 00:49:33.589
been a phenomenon.

00:49:33.589 --> 00:49:35.880
So if you go to a Kenyan
restaurant, you order a burger

00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:38.310
and fries, it's going
take a half an hour.

00:49:38.310 --> 00:49:41.522
But there's somebody
peeling the potato.

00:49:41.522 --> 00:49:42.480
It's going to be fresh.

00:49:42.480 --> 00:49:44.188
When you do get it,
it tastes really good

00:49:44.188 --> 00:49:45.840
because it's made fresh.

00:49:45.840 --> 00:49:49.230
So some of that's going away.

00:49:49.230 --> 00:49:51.360
It's like Americans are
trying to eat more healthy.

00:49:51.360 --> 00:49:52.020
Like red meat.

00:49:52.020 --> 00:49:53.850
I'm doing a story
about land issues,

00:49:53.850 --> 00:49:57.120
because Africa's population
is growing very fast.

00:49:57.120 --> 00:49:59.220
And Africans rely on land.

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:02.190
And there's going to be these
pressures on too many people,

00:50:02.190 --> 00:50:03.480
too little land.

00:50:03.480 --> 00:50:08.859
And so I was looking at
beef stats, because beef--

00:50:08.859 --> 00:50:09.900
I'm not like a hardcore--

00:50:09.900 --> 00:50:12.420
I eat beef, but a
lot of vegetarians

00:50:12.420 --> 00:50:16.500
will go on and on about the
resources that are needed

00:50:16.500 --> 00:50:19.620
to feed a beef cow, right?

00:50:19.620 --> 00:50:21.780
So the US and Europe,
they're decreasing the amount

00:50:21.780 --> 00:50:22.800
of red meat that we eat.

00:50:22.800 --> 00:50:24.674
Mostly for health reasons,
but other reasons.

00:50:24.674 --> 00:50:27.270
In Kenya, people now
have enough money

00:50:27.270 --> 00:50:30.210
to eat red meat,
which is a luxury.

00:50:30.210 --> 00:50:32.160
And so there's more
herds, there's more cows,

00:50:32.160 --> 00:50:33.030
and they need more space.

00:50:33.030 --> 00:50:34.821
And that's creating
all these other issues.

00:50:37.690 --> 00:50:40.380
So development brings
these complications,

00:50:40.380 --> 00:50:43.860
but overall, lifespans
are getting longer,

00:50:43.860 --> 00:50:46.170
kids are healthier, more
people are being educated,

00:50:46.170 --> 00:50:48.230
they have more
access to technology.

00:50:48.230 --> 00:50:50.199
In the urban areas, that's true.

00:50:50.199 --> 00:50:51.990
But at the same time,
you have these places

00:50:51.990 --> 00:50:54.660
like South Sudan, or Congo,
or Somalia that I cover.

00:50:54.660 --> 00:50:57.150
And they're stuck.

00:50:57.150 --> 00:50:59.370
They're not much
different from how

00:50:59.370 --> 00:51:03.550
they were 10, 15, 20 years ago.

00:51:03.550 --> 00:51:07.010
And those factors about bad
governance and conflict, that's

00:51:07.010 --> 00:51:09.780
still embedded in these places.

00:51:09.780 --> 00:51:12.480
So there's no quick solution.

00:51:12.480 --> 00:51:18.276
All the leadership in South
Sudan is has been tainted.

00:51:18.276 --> 00:51:19.400
That's putting it politely.

00:51:19.400 --> 00:51:20.650
They're all really bad.

00:51:20.650 --> 00:51:22.830
They're all pretty
brutal and corrupt.

00:51:22.830 --> 00:51:23.890
All of them.

00:51:23.890 --> 00:51:26.430
So you're going to need
another generation or two

00:51:26.430 --> 00:51:29.340
for these guys to fade
out before you have

00:51:29.340 --> 00:51:32.680
any hope of better leadership.

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:34.680
And then one thing I'll
bring up because we just

00:51:34.680 --> 00:51:38.580
have a few more minutes,
wildlife is a big issue.

00:51:38.580 --> 00:51:44.600
Because as these
populations grow,

00:51:44.600 --> 00:51:48.470
people need more space for
farms, for roads, for housing.

00:51:48.470 --> 00:51:53.300
And what you're seeing right now
is this onslaught on elephants,

00:51:53.300 --> 00:51:56.000
on rhinos, on
natural environments,

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:57.560
where these animals live.

00:51:57.560 --> 00:51:59.002
Sometimes, it's intentional.

00:51:59.002 --> 00:52:01.460
There are people that are going
out and poaching elephants,

00:52:01.460 --> 00:52:05.540
because the ivory, there's a
demand in China especially,

00:52:05.540 --> 00:52:07.880
but in other Asian
countries, for ivory.

00:52:07.880 --> 00:52:12.680
And that's pushing up the
price of elephant tusks.

00:52:12.680 --> 00:52:15.760
And so you get these
poor guys in Kenya

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:20.660
that maybe make $100 a
month, if that, $50 a month.

00:52:20.660 --> 00:52:23.090
And they can make
thousands of dollars

00:52:23.090 --> 00:52:25.040
by killing one elephant.

00:52:25.040 --> 00:52:28.760
And that's hard
economics to overcome.

00:52:28.760 --> 00:52:31.280
So right now as
we speak, there's

00:52:31.280 --> 00:52:34.340
been more elephants killed
in the last 10 years

00:52:34.340 --> 00:52:36.830
than a higher proportion
of the elephant population

00:52:36.830 --> 00:52:38.220
than ever before.

00:52:38.220 --> 00:52:39.110
And it's scary.

00:52:39.110 --> 00:52:41.930
Because it's a finite--

00:52:41.930 --> 00:52:43.680
there's a few 100,000
elephants left.

00:52:43.680 --> 00:52:44.630
That's it.

00:52:44.630 --> 00:52:47.759
And they only live in
these big, wild spaces.

00:52:47.759 --> 00:52:48.800
That's the direct threat.

00:52:48.800 --> 00:52:51.710
The indirect threat
is just development.

00:52:51.710 --> 00:52:52.550
I see it in Nairobi.

00:52:52.550 --> 00:52:54.680
The city is growing
into these areas that

00:52:54.680 --> 00:52:56.840
used to be rural or the bush.

00:52:56.840 --> 00:52:58.970
And now they have
housing neighborhoods

00:52:58.970 --> 00:53:00.680
on them, subdivisions.

00:53:00.680 --> 00:53:02.990
And there used to be wild
animals there, or farms.

00:53:02.990 --> 00:53:07.470
And so there's going to be
some problems with that.

00:53:07.470 --> 00:53:09.570
And they're hard
choices to make.

00:53:09.570 --> 00:53:10.820
You have a growing population.

00:53:10.820 --> 00:53:11.819
You need to feed people.

00:53:11.819 --> 00:53:14.840
Do you set aside land
that could be farmed

00:53:14.840 --> 00:53:17.030
and say "no, you're not
allowed to farm that.

00:53:17.030 --> 00:53:18.500
That's where elephants live."

00:53:18.500 --> 00:53:20.630
Or do you just kick
off all the elephants,

00:53:20.630 --> 00:53:25.460
or kill them off, and then say
we need to use that for a farm.

00:53:25.460 --> 00:53:26.550
Those are hard questions.

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:31.179
Yes, sir.

00:53:31.179 --> 00:53:32.470
AUDIENCE: It's about Al-Shabab.

00:53:32.470 --> 00:53:34.225
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: Yes.

00:53:34.225 --> 00:53:37.430
AUDIENCE: Seems like the peak
was the Westgate terrorist act,

00:53:37.430 --> 00:53:41.779
and from then it
glimpses, but I actually

00:53:41.779 --> 00:53:43.570
am not current on where
they are right now.

00:53:43.570 --> 00:53:45.435
I know they're shutting down--
but there's talk about shutting

00:53:45.435 --> 00:53:47.160
down Dadaab, the refugee camp--

00:53:47.160 --> 00:53:48.811
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: Right.

00:53:48.811 --> 00:53:49.310
No, no.

00:53:49.310 --> 00:53:52.360
That's a good-- let me knock
on wood as I answer this,

00:53:52.360 --> 00:53:53.810
because they've been down.

00:53:53.810 --> 00:53:55.810
They've been down over
the last couple of years,

00:53:55.810 --> 00:53:57.310
but they were down
before Westgate,

00:53:57.310 --> 00:53:58.730
which was what was scary.

00:53:58.730 --> 00:54:02.050
So the Westgate Mall
was a big mall in Kenya.

00:54:02.050 --> 00:54:04.980
In 2013, these four
guys came in there,

00:54:04.980 --> 00:54:07.510
part of an Islamic group,
and they just started machine

00:54:07.510 --> 00:54:09.820
gunning shoppers and civilians.

00:54:09.820 --> 00:54:11.950
And then they took over
them all for a few hours

00:54:11.950 --> 00:54:15.660
until they were kicked out and
about 100 people were killed.

00:54:15.660 --> 00:54:22.110
Kids, shoppers, just ordinary
people, terrorist attack.

00:54:22.110 --> 00:54:23.692
They had been quiet before that.

00:54:23.692 --> 00:54:25.150
And everybody was
saying, "oh yeah,

00:54:25.150 --> 00:54:26.233
what happened the Shabab?"

00:54:26.233 --> 00:54:28.270
And all of a sudden,
boom, one of the worst

00:54:28.270 --> 00:54:31.550
terrorist incidents in
recent memory anywhere.

00:54:31.550 --> 00:54:33.170
They're under a lot of pressure.

00:54:33.170 --> 00:54:36.410
The US has done a
good job of killing

00:54:36.410 --> 00:54:38.570
the leaders with drone
strikes and air strikes.

00:54:38.570 --> 00:54:41.660
They've struggled for years
to get good intelligence,

00:54:41.660 --> 00:54:44.180
and they now seem to have
it, because they're hitting--

00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:45.950
they're killing the leaders.

00:54:45.950 --> 00:54:48.230
But it's a big group.

00:54:48.230 --> 00:54:50.510
Somalia has really
bad governance,

00:54:50.510 --> 00:54:53.780
and is just an open space
where you can do anything.

00:54:53.780 --> 00:54:57.010
So they're still there.

00:54:57.010 --> 00:55:00.390
My guess is, they're
on the decline,

00:55:00.390 --> 00:55:03.840
but they're capable of
doing some more nasty stuff.

00:55:03.840 --> 00:55:06.630
And it's just kind of
a miracle that they

00:55:06.630 --> 00:55:10.387
haven't attacked a big
Western target or an embassy.

00:55:10.387 --> 00:55:11.970
Because that's who
they really don't--

00:55:11.970 --> 00:55:13.710
that's who they're fighting.

00:55:13.710 --> 00:55:15.210
The US is killing the leaders.

00:55:15.210 --> 00:55:19.680
Why aren't they trying
to kill Americans?

00:55:19.680 --> 00:55:20.480
They probably are.

00:55:20.480 --> 00:55:22.880
It's just harder because the
American embassy in Nairobi

00:55:22.880 --> 00:55:24.300
is a fortress.

00:55:24.300 --> 00:55:25.710
So that's not an easy target.

00:55:25.710 --> 00:55:28.250
The mall is a much
better target.

00:55:28.250 --> 00:55:31.380
Dadaab, they've cooled off
on trying to close that.

00:55:31.380 --> 00:55:33.870
The Kenyan government
really wanted to close that,

00:55:33.870 --> 00:55:36.530
and they have been
sort of smacked back.

00:55:36.530 --> 00:55:39.600
And their own courts
said, "no, it's

00:55:39.600 --> 00:55:42.270
illegal to kick these guys out
because you've recognized them

00:55:42.270 --> 00:55:44.520
as refugees."

00:55:44.520 --> 00:55:46.650
And all the donors
who pay for Dadaab

00:55:46.650 --> 00:55:49.050
are like, "we're not
giving you a cent

00:55:49.050 --> 00:55:51.310
to relocate these people."

00:55:51.310 --> 00:55:52.474
So they could do it.

00:55:52.474 --> 00:55:53.890
Physically, they
could go in there

00:55:53.890 --> 00:55:56.160
and push people out at gunpoint.

00:55:56.160 --> 00:55:58.170
But they would
take so much crap,

00:55:58.170 --> 00:56:00.730
and even their own courts
have said that's illegal.

00:56:00.730 --> 00:56:03.900
So I don't think
that's going to change.

00:56:03.900 --> 00:56:05.830
I think those people
are stuck there.

00:56:05.830 --> 00:56:07.080
There's three generations now.

00:56:07.080 --> 00:56:08.250
There's people that are--

00:56:08.250 --> 00:56:10.080
there's grandchildren,
people that

00:56:10.080 --> 00:56:12.510
came there as really
little kids, then had kids,

00:56:12.510 --> 00:56:15.630
and then those kids had kids.

00:56:15.630 --> 00:56:16.440
It's permanent.

00:56:19.390 --> 00:56:19.891
And--

00:56:19.891 --> 00:56:22.390
SPEAKER: We have time for one
more question, which I'll ask.

00:56:22.390 --> 00:56:23.490
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: Please.

00:56:23.490 --> 00:56:25.573
SPEAKER: So there are
obviously many ups and downs

00:56:25.573 --> 00:56:26.840
to being a journalist.

00:56:26.840 --> 00:56:28.600
You were once a
young journalist,

00:56:28.600 --> 00:56:29.910
aspiring journalist.

00:56:29.910 --> 00:56:32.060
What advice would you have
given your younger self?

00:56:32.060 --> 00:56:34.435
What do you know now that you
wish you'd known back then?

00:56:34.435 --> 00:56:37.262
JEFFREY GETTLEMAN: God,
that's why I wrote that book.

00:56:37.262 --> 00:56:39.470
And nobody is allowed to
leave here without the book,

00:56:39.470 --> 00:56:40.220
because it's free.

00:56:43.940 --> 00:56:46.100
I wish I had balanced
things better.

00:56:46.100 --> 00:56:50.060
I wish I had not put so
much pressure on myself

00:56:50.060 --> 00:56:53.510
to succeed professionally
that I made bad decisions

00:56:53.510 --> 00:56:55.280
for my personal life.

00:56:55.280 --> 00:56:59.870
Because when you're
young, you're torn.

00:56:59.870 --> 00:57:02.510
Part of you is just desperate
to prove yourself and show

00:57:02.510 --> 00:57:06.230
that you can be successful
and do something of value.

00:57:06.230 --> 00:57:07.730
But another part
of you just wants

00:57:07.730 --> 00:57:10.910
to have fun and get
close to people.

00:57:10.910 --> 00:57:13.670
And before you have kids,
you have this opportunity

00:57:13.670 --> 00:57:16.010
to enjoy the world
with somebody.

00:57:16.010 --> 00:57:17.480
And that's a special time.

00:57:17.480 --> 00:57:20.030
As you go on in life,
it's harder and harder

00:57:20.030 --> 00:57:24.500
to have that opportunity
to just fall in love

00:57:24.500 --> 00:57:26.180
and honor that love.

00:57:26.180 --> 00:57:28.609
And so I think as
a young person,

00:57:28.609 --> 00:57:30.650
I was like probably a lot
of people in this room.

00:57:30.650 --> 00:57:32.240
I was really driven
professionally,

00:57:32.240 --> 00:57:35.450
and I put a lot of
pressure on myself.

00:57:35.450 --> 00:57:38.720
And I should have just
chilled out and been like,

00:57:38.720 --> 00:57:41.420
"it'll work out."

00:57:41.420 --> 00:57:45.230
And I should have honored my
personal side of my life more.

00:57:45.230 --> 00:57:47.120
Because you don't
get that time back.

00:57:47.120 --> 00:57:50.220
You're only like
20 or 25 like once.

00:57:50.220 --> 00:57:51.420
And then it's done.

00:57:51.420 --> 00:57:54.370
And so just to
keep that balance.

00:57:54.370 --> 00:57:56.390
But it would have been hard.

00:57:56.390 --> 00:57:58.010
You know what I mean?

00:57:58.010 --> 00:57:59.720
I had to make a
lot of sacrifices

00:57:59.720 --> 00:58:02.330
for my job to be standing
here talking to you guys,

00:58:02.330 --> 00:58:04.670
some of those sacrifices
were probably necessary.

00:58:04.670 --> 00:58:10.770
But I think I could have had
a little more perspective.

00:58:10.770 --> 00:58:11.520
And I didn't.

00:58:11.520 --> 00:58:13.675
I was really singularly focused.

